INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2020c310-c605-4f12-90a8-c2df8f7ce11f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$FastAPI Routing — Route Parameters, Groups, and APIRouter Prefixes$escape$,
  $escape$FastAPI routes are defined by decorating async (or sync) functions with `@app.get`, `@app.post`, etc. Path parameters are declared with curly braces and typed in the function signature — FastAPI validates and coerces them automatically. Query parameters are any function parameters not in the path.

For larger apps, `APIRouter` is the core grouping primitive. You instantiate a router per domain, define routes on it, then register it on the main `FastAPI` instance via `app.include_router()`. The `prefix` argument on `include_router` prepends a path segment to every route in that router — no need to repeat `/users` on every handler. `tags` groups endpoints in the auto-generated OpenAPI docs.

Nested routers are supported: a router can `include_router` another router, composing prefixes. Dependency injection works identically on `APIRouter` as on `app`, so you can attach auth middleware at the router level rather than per-route. Path parameter types (`int`, `UUID`, `Enum`) are enforced by Pydantic before the handler runs.$escape$,
  $escape$from fastapi import APIRouter, FastAPI
from uuid import UUID

router = APIRouter(prefix="/users", tags=["users"])

@router.get("/{user_id}")
async def get_user(user_id: UUID):
    return {"user_id": user_id}

@router.get("/{user_id}/posts")
async def get_user_posts(user_id: UUID, limit: int = 10):
    return {"user_id": user_id, "limit": limit}

app = FastAPI()
app.include_router(router)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
