INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9d7ab4fe-c877-47e9-adcd-1a4963bd767d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$FastAPI + SQLAlchemy — N+1 Prevention, ORMs vs Core, and Alembic Migrations$escape$,
  $escape$FastAPI pairs most naturally with SQLAlchemy — either its ORM layer or Core (query builder style). The ORM handles relationship mapping, but lazy loading is disabled by default in async SQLAlchemy's `AsyncSession`. That's intentional: it forces explicit loading and eliminates N+1 at the source.

When loading `Post` objects with their `comments`, pass `selectinload(Post.comments)` to your `select()`. Skip it and accessing `post.comments` in an async context raises `MissingGreenlet` — SQLAlchemy refuses silent lazy loads under `asyncio`. `joinedload` works too but produces a single JOIN; prefer `selectinload` for one-to-many to avoid row duplication.

SQLAlchemy Core fits complex reporting or bulk operations where you want raw SQL control without ORM overhead — use `text()` or `select()` directly against table objects.

For migrations, Alembic hooks into your `Base.metadata`. Run `alembic revision --autogenerate -m "description"` after model changes, but always audit the output — autogenerate misses `server_default` changes, constraint renames, and enum alterations.

SQLModel (SQLAlchemy + Pydantic in one class) cuts boilerplate but obscures what SQLAlchemy is doing underneath. Worth knowing the layer you're abstracting.$escape$,
  $escape$from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession
from sqlalchemy.orm import selectinload
from sqlalchemy import select
from app.models import Post

async def get_posts_with_comments(db: AsyncSession) -> list[Post]:
    result = await db.execute(
        select(Post)
        .options(selectinload(Post.comments))
        .where(Post.is_published == True)
        .order_by(Post.created_at.desc())
    )
    return result.scalars().all()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
