INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f9a9dcbd-8d3e-499b-a9ef-bbe09de0b7ba',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$FastAPI Auto-Docs — What /docs Actually Gives You and How to Control It$escape$,
  $escape$FastAPI generates interactive OpenAPI documentation at /docs (Swagger UI) and /redoc automatically — zero configuration required. Every route, path parameter, query parameter, request body, and response model is introspected at startup via Python type hints and Pydantic models.

The docs aren't just cosmetic. FastAPI reads your `response_model`, `status_code`, and `responses` kwargs to build accurate schema definitions. Declare `response_model=UserOut` and the schema reflects exactly what clients receive — not what's stored internally.

You can tag routes with `tags=["users"]` for grouping, add `summary` and `description` per endpoint, and attach `openapi_extra` for anything FastAPI doesn't natively support (e.g. custom security schemes).

To exclude sensitive internal routes from the docs entirely, set `include_in_schema=False` on the route decorator. To disable the docs UI in production while keeping the OpenAPI JSON available, pass `docs_url=None` to `FastAPI()` and serve `/openapi.json` on a restricted path.

The schema is generated once at startup from `app.openapi()` — you can override that method to inject custom metadata, merge external specs, or mutate the schema dict directly.$escape$,
  $escape$from fastapi import FastAPI
from pydantic import BaseModel

app = FastAPI(docs_url="/docs", redoc_url=None)

class UserOut(BaseModel):
    id: int
    username: str

@app.get(
    "/users/{user_id}",
    response_model=UserOut,
    tags=["users"],
    summary="Fetch a user by ID",
    responses={404: {"description": "User not found"}},
)
async def get_user(user_id: int):
    return {"id": user_id, "username": "alice"}

@app.get("/internal/health", include_in_schema=False)
async def health():
    return {"status": "ok"}$escape$,
